  "suggestion": "[neuroscience+Bayesian-inference+Karl-Friston+information-theory+active-inference] IMPLEMENT NOW — Active Inference Engine (minimal TypeScript). This idea has been refined to convergence across 6+ cycles. Concrete spec: Person carries `beliefs: Record<string, number>` (prior probabilities) and `precision: Record<string, number>` (inverse variance = confidence). For each stimulus, compute prediction error PE = |observation - belief|, weighted by precision. If PE × precision > action_threshold → generate action to change world (active inference). If PE × precision ≤ action_threshold → update belief (perceptual inference). Free energy F = PE² × precision - log(precision). Response emotion = sign(PE) × magnitude(PE × precision). This unifies surprise, curiosity, anxiety, and relief as a single free-energy signal, and explains why high-precision priors (trauma, rigid beliefs) resist updating. Replace the current rootCauseType heuristics with F-minimization as the universal decision rule. — Math: F = ΣD_KL[q(s)||p(s|o)] — minimize divergence between beliefs and posterior given observations; action chosen to make observations match predictions; [behavioral-psychology+neuroscience+dynamical-systems+addiction-theory] NEW — Opponent Process Dynamics (Solomon & Corbit 1974). Every affective response consists of two competing processes: a primary process a(t) that mirrors the stimulus and a slower opponent process b(t) that opposes it. Net affect = a(t) − b(t). With repetition, b strengthens (habituation/tolerance) while a stays constant → hedonic adaptation. On stimulus removal, b outlasts a → affective contrast (withdrawal, post-vacation blues, relief after fear). Add to person state: `opponentStrength: Record<stimulus_type, number>` that increments each exposure. Response valence = primaryResponse × (1 − opponentStrength). Explains addiction, boredom, emotional contrast, why the 10th compliment feels hollow, and why recovery from loss overshoots into joy. — Math: a(t) = A·e^(-α·t), b(t) = B_n·e^(-β·t) where B_n grows with n exposures; net affect = a(t) − b(t); B_n = B_0·(1 − e^(-γn)); [information-theory+psychophysiology+Berlyne-arousal-theory+personality-psychology+dynamical-systems] NEW — Psychological Entropy Regulation as Arousal Drive (Berlyne 1960 + Shannon entropy). Compute Shannon entropy H of the person's current belief state: H = −Σ p_i · log(p_i). Humans maintain entropy in a target band [H_min, H_max] specific to their personality (sensation-seekers have higher H_max; anxious individuals lower H_max). When H < H_min → boredom → exploration/curiosity/risk-seeking behavior. When H > H_max → overwhelm/anxiety → routine-seeking/simplification/withdrawal. Behavior type is determined by entropy delta, not content. This unifies: curiosity (undercertainty), anxiety (overcertainty collapse), flow state (H in optimal band), decision fatigue (entropy overload), and why trauma creates rigid low-entropy worlds. Connects naturally to Active Inference: F-minimization that overshoots creates boredom; F that fails to converge creates anxiety. — Math: H(beliefs) = −Σ p_i log p_i; drive_toward_novelty = ReLU(H_target − H); drive_toward_routine = ReLU(H − H_target); net arousal_motive = drive_toward_novelty − drive_toward_routine",
